    "recap_headline": "Long Beach State University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "LOS ANGELES, Calif.\n-- Long Beach State (4-12, 0-3) stayed within striking distance through the middle innings Tuesday night but fell 1-6\u00a0to No. 25 USC Trojans (16-0, 3-0) at Dedeaux Field, where USC is playing on its newly renovated home field during the 2026 season. The Dirtbags held the Trojans scoreless in five innings and received strong relief work after an early USC surge.\nLong Beach State opened the night by matching USC through the first inning after\nVan Larson\nretired the Trojans in order, including a strikeout to begin the bottom half. USC broke through in the second when Kevin Takeuchi doubled and Andrew Lamb followed later in the inning with a three-run home run to right field for a 3-0 lead.\nThe Trojans added one more in the third after Abbrie Covarrubias led off with a ground-rule double and Maximo Martinez drove him in with a single to center, extending the lead to 4-0. Larson worked 2.2 innings before\nBrad Grindlinger\nentered to strand two runners and limit further damage in the inning.\nThe Dirtbags answered in the fourth.\nJake Evans\nsingled to center, moved to second on a wild pitch and advanced to third on a flyout before\nDylan Lina\nlined a two-out RBI single to right field, cutting the deficit to 4-1. Long Beach State threatened again in the sixth when\nTrevor Goldenetz\nsingled and Evans reached after being hit by a pitch, putting two aboard with one out, but USC escaped the inning to hold the three-run advantage.\nLong Beach State's bullpen kept USC quiet through the middle frames.\nJoey Iglesias\ndelivered 2.2 hitless innings with two strikeouts, while\nCaleb Anderson\nadded a scoreless seventh inning. USC added two insurance runs in the eighth on a sacrifice fly and RBI double before the Dirtbags were retired in order in the ninth.\nEvans finished 1-for-2, scored the Dirtbags' lone run and reached base three times after being hit twice. Goldenetz and Lina also recorded hits, with Lina driving in Long Beach State's only run.\nOn the mound Long Beach State received effective bullpen work after the early innings, with\nJoey Iglesias\nand\nCaleb Anderson\ncombining for 3.2 scoreless innings to keep the Dirtbags within reach late. Iglesias retired eight of the nine batters he faced over 2.2 hitless innings with two strikeouts, while Anderson added a clean seventh inning with one strikeout.\nVan Larson\ntook the loss after allowing four runs over 2.2 innings, and\nBrad Grindlinger\nbridged the third by stranding inherited runners before\nTyler Gebb\nworked the eighth inning.\nLong Beach State returns to Big West Conference play this weekend against Hawai?i Rainbow Warriors baseball at Bohl Diamond at Blair Field. First pitch for Friday's opener is scheduled for 6:05 p.m., with the game streaming on ESPN+."
